<section class="mission-details">
	<div class="mission-intro">
		
		<a name="eztoc19727164_1" id="eztoc19727164_1"></a><h2><b>The mission</b></h2><p>The Copernicus Sentinel-1 mission is designed as a two-satellite constellation. Each satellite&nbsp;carries an advanced radar instrument to provide an all-weather, day-and-night supply of imagery of Earthâ€™s surface. The mission <b><a href="https://www.esa.int/Applications/Observing_the_Earth/Copernicus/Sentinel-1/Mission_ends_for_Copernicus_Sentinel-1B_satellite" target="_blank">ended</a></b> for Sentinel-1B in 2022.</p>
	</div>
	<div class="mission-data">
		
		<a name="eztoc19728187_1" id="eztoc19728187_1"></a><h2><b>The launch</b></h2>
<ul>

<li>
<b>Date:&nbsp;</b>Sentinel-1A - 03 April 2014&nbsp;<br />
&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Sentinel-1B - 25 April 2016&nbsp;<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Sentinel-1C - 2024&nbsp;</li>

<li><b>Site:&nbsp;</b>Kourou, French Guiana</li>

<li>
<b>Rocket:&nbsp;</b>Sentinel-1A and -B on Soyuz&nbsp;<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Sentinel-1C on Vega-C&nbsp;</li>

</ul>

	</div>
	</section>

<section class="mission-stats connecting-benefiting">
	
		
		
<ul>

<li><a href="https://www.esa.int/Applications/Observing_the_Earth/Copernicus/Sentinel-1/Introducing_Sentinel-1" target="_blank"><b>1st</b></a>&nbsp;in the Sentinel series</li>

<li><a href="https://www.esa.int/Applications/Observing_the_Earth/Copernicus/Sentinel-1/Satellite_constellation" target="_blank"><b>693 km</b></a>&nbsp;orbit altitude</li>

<li><a href="https://www.esa.int/Applications/Observing_the_Earth/Copernicus/Sentinel-1/Facts_and_figures" target="_blank"><b>7 years </b></a>mission life</li>

</ul>

	
